<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8"><title>Ozone Overview</title><link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/+static/base.HLL9TqKl0YYybSzmT_wTdw.cache.css" /><link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/+static/doc.MXicahAOcEleYTBJrPykiw.cache.css" /><link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/+static/prettify/prettify.pZ5FqzM6cPxAflH0va2Ucw.cache.css" /></head><body class="Site"><header class="Site-header "><div class="Header"><div class="Header-title"></div></div></header><div class="Site-content Site-Content--markdown"><div class="Container"><div class="doc"><h1><a class="h" name="Ozone-Overview" href="#Ozone-Overview"><span></span></a>Ozone Overview</h1><p>Ozone is a platform abstraction layer beneath the Aura window system that is used for low level input and graphics. Once complete, the abstraction will support underlying systems ranging from embedded SoC targets to new X11-alternative window systems on Linux such as Wayland or Mir to bring up Aura Chromium by providing an implementation of the platform interface.</p><h2><a class="h" name="Guiding-Principles" href="#Guiding-Principles"><span></span></a>Guiding Principles</h2><p>Our goal is to enable chromium to be used in a wide variety of projects by making porting to new platforms easy. To support this goal, ozone follows the following principles:</p><ol><li><strong>Interfaces, not ifdefs</strong>. Differences between platforms are handled by calling a platform-supplied object through an interface instead of using conditional compilation. Platform internals remain encapsulated, and the public interface acts as a firewall between the platform-neutral upper layers (aura, blink, content, etc) and the platform-specific lower layers. The platform layer is relatively centralized to minimize the number of places ports need to add code.</li><li><strong>Flexible interfaces</strong>. The platform interfaces should encapsulate just what chrome needs from the platform, with minimal constraints on the platform&#39;s implementation as well as minimal constraints on usage from upper layers. An overly prescriptive interface is less useful for porting because fewer ports will be able to use it unmodified. Another way of stating is that the platform layer should provide mechanism, not policy.</li><li><strong>Runtime binding of platforms</strong>. Avoiding conditional compilation in the upper layers allows us to build multiple platforms into one binary and bind them at runtime. We allow this and provide a command-line flag to select a platform (<code class="code">--ozone-platform</code>) if multiple are enabled. Each platform has a unique build define (e.g. <code class="code">ozone_platform_foo</code>) that can be turned on or off independently.</li><li><strong>Easy out-of-tree platforms</strong>. Most ports begin as forks. Some of them later merge their code upstream, others will have an extended life out of tree. This is OK, and we should make this process easy to encourage ports, and to encourage frequent gardening of chromium changes into the downstream project. If gardening an out-of-tree port is hard, then those projects will simply ship outdated and potentially insecure chromium-derived code to users. One way we support these projects is by providing a way to inject additional platforms into the build by only patching one <code class="code">ozone_extra.gni</code> file.</li></ol><h2><a class="h" name="Ozone-Platform-Interface" href="#Ozone-Platform-Interface"><span></span></a>Ozone Platform Interface</h2><p>Ozone moves platform-specific code behind the following interfaces:</p><ul><li><code class="code">PlatformWindow</code> represents a window in the windowing system underlying chrome. Interaction with the windowing system (resize, maximize, close, etc) as well as dispatch of input events happens via this interface. Under aura, a <code class="code">PlatformWindow</code> corresponds to a <code class="code">WindowTreeHost</code>. Under mojo, it corresponds to a <code class="code">NativeViewport</code>. On bare hardware, the underlying windowing system is very simple and a platform window corresponds to a physical display.</li><li><code class="code">SurfaceFactoryOzone</code> is used to create surfaces for the Chrome compositor to paint on using EGL/GLES2 or Skia.</li><li><code class="code">GpuPlatformSupportHost</code> provides the platform code access to IPC between the browser &amp; GPU processes. Some platforms need this to provide additional services in the GPU process such as display configuration.</li><li><code class="code">CursorFactoryOzone</code> is used to load &amp; set platform cursors.</li><li><code class="code">OverlayManagerOzone</code> is used to manage overlays.</li><li><code class="code">InputController</code> allows to control input devices such as keyboard, mouse or touchpad.</li><li><code class="code">SystemInputInjector</code> converts input into events and injects them to the Ozone platform.</li><li><code class="code">NativeDisplayDelegate</code> is used to support display configuration &amp; hotplug.</li></ul><h2><a class="h" name="Ozone-in-Chromium" href="#Ozone-in-Chromium"><span></span></a>Ozone in Chromium</h2><p>Our implementation of Ozone required changes concentrated in these areas:</p><ul><li>Cleaning up extensive assumptions about use of X11 throughout the tree, protecting this code behind the <code class="code">USE_X11</code> ifdef, and adding a new <code class="code">USE_OZONE</code> path that works in a relatively platform-neutral way by delegating to the interfaces described above.</li><li>a <code class="code">WindowTreeHostOzone</code> to send events into Aura and participate in display management on the host system, and</li><li>an Ozone-specific flavor of <code class="code">GLSurfaceEGL</code> which delegates allocation of accelerated surfaces and refresh syncing to the provided implementation of <code class="code">SurfaceFactoryOzone</code>.</li></ul><h2><a class="h" name="Porting-with-Ozone" href="#Porting-with-Ozone"><span></span></a>Porting with Ozone</h2><p>Users of the Ozone abstraction need to do the following, at minimum:</p><ul><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">PlatformWindow</code>. This class (I&#39;ll call it <code class="code">PlatformWindowImpl</code>) is responsible for window system integration. It can use <code class="code">MessagePumpLibevent</code> to poll for events from file descriptors and then invoke <code class="code">PlatformWindowDelegate::DispatchEvent</code> to dispatch each event.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">SurfaceFactoryOzone</code> that handles allocating accelerated surfaces. I&#39;ll call this <code class="code">SurfaceFactoryOzoneImpl</code>.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">CursorFactoryOzone</code> to manage cursors, or use the <code class="code">BitmapCursorFactoryOzone</code> implementation if only bitmap cursors need to be supported.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">OverlayManagerOzone</code> or just use <code class="code">StubOverlayManager</code> if your platform does not support overlays.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">NativeDisplayDelegate</code> if necessary or just use <code class="code">FakeDisplayDelegate</code>.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">GpuPlatformSupportHost</code> or just use <code class="code">StubGpuPlatformSupportHost</code>.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">InputController</code> or just use <code class="code">StubInputController</code>.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">SystemInputInjector</code> if necessary.</li><li>Write a subclass of <code class="code">OzonePlatform</code> that owns instances of the above subclasses and provide a static constructor function for these objects. This constructor will be called when your platform is selected and the returned objects will be used to provide implementations of all the ozone platform interfaces. If your platform does not need some of the interfaces then you can just return a <code class="code">Stub*</code> instance or a <code class="code">nullptr</code>.</li></ul><h2><a class="h" name="Adding-an-Ozone-Platform-to-the-build-instructions-for-out_of_tree-ports" href="#Adding-an-Ozone-Platform-to-the-build-instructions-for-out_of_tree-ports"><span></span></a>Adding an Ozone Platform to the build (instructions for out-of-tree ports)</h2><p>The recommended way to add your platform to the build is as follows. This walks through creating a new ozone platform called <code class="code">foo</code>.</p><ol><li>Fork <code class="code">chromium/src.git</code>.</li><li>Add your implementation in <code class="code">ui/ozone/platform/</code> alongside internal platforms.</li><li>Patch <code class="code">ui/ozone/ozone_extra.gni</code> to add your <code class="code">foo</code> platform.</li></ol><h2><a class="h" name="Building-with-Ozone" href="#Building-with-Ozone"><span></span></a>Building with Ozone</h2><h3><a class="h" name="Chrome-OS-waterfall" href="#Chrome-OS-waterfall"><span></span></a>Chrome OS - (<a href="https://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.chromiumos/waterfall?builder=Linux+ChromiumOS+Ozone+Builder&amp;builder=Linux+ChromiumOS+Ozone+Tests+%281%29&amp;builder=Linux+ChromiumOS+Ozone+Tests+%282%29&amp;reload=none">waterfall</a>)</h3><p>To build <code class="code">chrome</code>, do this from the <code class="code">src</code> directory:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pln">gn args </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneChromeOS</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">args</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="str">&quot;use_ozone=true target_os=\&quot;chromeos\&quot;&quot;</span><span class="pln">
ninja </span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">C </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneChromeOS</span><span class="pln"> chrome
</span></pre><p>Then to run for example the X11 platform:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pun">.</span><span class="str">/out/</span><span class="typ">OzoneChromeOS</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="pln">chrome </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">platform</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">x11
</span></pre><h3><a class="h" name="Embedded" href="#Embedded"><span></span></a>Embedded</h3><p><strong>Warning: Only some targets such as <code class="code">content_shell</code> or unit tests are currently working for embedded builds.</strong></p><p>To build <code class="code">content_shell</code>, do this from the <code class="code">src</code> directory:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pln">gn args </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneEmbedded</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">args</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="str">&quot;use_ozone=true toolkit_views=false&quot;</span><span class="pln">
ninja </span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">C </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneEmbedded</span><span class="pln"> content_shell
</span></pre><p>Then to run for example the headless platform:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pun">.</span><span class="str">/out/</span><span class="typ">OzoneEmbedded</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="pln">content_shell </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">platform</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">headless \
                                  </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="kwd">dump</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">file</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="str">/tmp/</span><span class="pln">
</span></pre><h3><a class="h" name="Linux-Desktop-waterfall" href="#Linux-Desktop-waterfall"><span></span></a>Linux Desktop - (<a href="https://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.fyi/builders/Ozone%20Linux/">waterfall</a>)</h3><p><strong>Warning: Experimental support for Linux Desktop is available since m57 but this is still <a href="https://crbug.com/295089">in development</a> and currently has many bugs.</strong></p><p>To build <code class="code">chrome</code>, do this from the <code class="code">src</code> directory:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pln">gn args </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneLinuxDesktop</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">args</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="str">&quot;use_ozone=true enable_package_mash_services=true&quot;</span><span class="pln">
ninja </span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">C </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneLinuxDesktop</span><span class="pln"> chrome
</span></pre><p>Then to run for example the X11 platform:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pun">.</span><span class="str">/out/</span><span class="typ">OzoneLinuxDesktop</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="pln">chrome </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">platform</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">x11 \
                               </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">mash \
                               </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">window</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">manager</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">simple_wm
</span></pre><h3><a class="h" name="GN-Configuration-notes" href="#GN-Configuration-notes"><span></span></a>GN Configuration notes</h3><p>You can turn properly implemented ozone platforms on and off by setting the corresponding flags in your GN configuration. For example <code class="code">ozone_platform_headless=false ozone_platform_gbm=false</code> will turn off the headless and DRM/GBM platforms. This will result in a smaller binary and faster builds. To turn ALL platforms off by default, set <code class="code">ozone_auto_platforms=false</code>.</p><p>You can also specify a default platform to run by setting the <code class="code">ozone_platform</code> build parameter. For example <code class="code">ozone_platform=&quot;x11&quot;</code> will make X11 the default platform when <code class="code">--ozone-platform</code> is not passed to the program. If <code class="code">ozone_auto_platforms</code> is true then <code class="code">ozone_platform</code> is set to <code class="code">headless</code> by default.</p><h2><a class="h" name="Running-with-Ozone" href="#Running-with-Ozone"><span></span></a>Running with Ozone</h2><p>Specify the platform you want to use at runtime using the <code class="code">--ozone-platform</code> flag. For example, to run <code class="code">content_shell</code> with the GBM platform:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pln">content_shell </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">platform</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">gbm
</span></pre><p>Caveats:</p><ul><li><code class="code">content_shell</code> always runs at 800x600 resolution.</li><li>For the GBM platform, you may need to terminate your X server (or any other display server) prior to testing.</li><li>During development, you may need to configure <a href="linux_sandboxing.md">sandboxing</a> or to disable it.</li></ul><h2><a class="h" name="Ozone-Platforms" href="#Ozone-Platforms"><span></span></a>Ozone Platforms</h2><h3><a class="h" name="Headless" href="#Headless"><span></span></a>Headless</h3><p>This platform draws graphical output to a PNG image (no GPU support; software rendering only) and will not output to the screen. You can set the path of the directory where to output the images by specifying <code class="code">--ozone-dump-file=/path/to/output-directory</code> on the command line:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pln">content_shell </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">platform</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">headless \
              </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="kwd">dump</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">file</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="str">/tmp/</span><span class="pln">
</span></pre><h3><a class="h" name="DRM_GBM" href="#DRM_GBM"><span></span></a>DRM/GBM</h3><p>This is Linux direct rending with acceleration via mesa GBM &amp; linux DRM/KMS (EGL/GLES2 accelerated rendering &amp; modesetting in GPU process) and is in production use on <a href="https://www.chromium.org/chromium-os">Chrome OS</a>.</p><p>Note that all Chrome OS builds of Chrome will compile and attempt to use this. See <a href="https://www.chromium.org/chromium-os/how-tos-and-troubleshooting/building-chromium-browser">Building Chromium for Chromium OS</a> for build instructions.</p><h3><a class="h" name="Cast" href="#Cast"><span></span></a>Cast</h3><p>This platform is used for <a href="https://www.google.com/intl/en_us/chromecast/">Chromecast</a>.</p><h3><a class="h" name="X11" href="#X11"><span></span></a>X11</h3><p>This platform provides support for the <a href="https://www.x.org/">X window system</a>.</p><h3><a class="h" name="Wayland" href="#Wayland"><span></span></a>Wayland</h3><p>This platform provides support for the <a href="http://wayland.freedesktop.org/">Wayland</a> display protocol. It was initially developed by Intel as <a href="https://github.com/01org/ozone-wayland">a fork of chromium</a> and then partially upstreamed. It is still actively being developed in the chromium tree, feel free to discuss with us on freenode.net, <code class="code">#ozone-wayland</code> channel or on <code class="code">ozone-dev</code>.</p><p>Below are some quick build &amp; run instructions. It is assumed that you are launching <code class="code">chrome</code> from a Wayland environment such as <code class="code">weston</code>. Execute the following commands:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pln">gn args </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneWayland</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">args</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="str">&quot;use_ozone=true enable_package_mash_services=true&quot;</span><span class="pln">
ninja </span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">C </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneWayland</span><span class="pln"> chrome
</span><span class="pun">./</span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneWayland</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="pln">chrome </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">ozone</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">platform</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">wayland \
                          </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">mash \
                          </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">window</span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">manager</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln">simple_wm
</span></pre><h3><a class="h" name="Caca" href="#Caca"><span></span></a>Caca</h3><p>This platform draws graphical output to text using <a href="http://caca.zoy.org/wiki/libcaca">libcaca</a> (no GPU support; software rendering only). In case you ever wanted to test embedded content shell on tty. It has been <a href="https://codereview.chromium.org/2445323002/">removed from the tree</a> and is no longer maintained but you can <a href="https://github.com/fred-wang/ozone-caca">build it as an out-of-tree port</a>.</p><p>Alternatively, you can try the latest revision known to work. First, install libcaca shared library and development files. Next, move to the git revision <code class="code">0e64be9cf335ee3bea7c989702c5a9a0934af037</code> (you will probably need to synchronize the build dependencies with <code class="code">gclient sync --with_branch_heads</code>). Finally, build and run the caca platform with the following commands:</p><pre class="code"><span class="pln">gn args </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneCaca</span><span class="pln"> \
        </span><span class="pun">--</span><span class="pln">args</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="str">&quot;use_ozone=true ozone_platform_caca=true use_sysroot=false ozone_auto_platforms=false toolkit_views=false&quot;</span><span class="pln">
ninja </span><span class="pun">-</span><span class="pln">C </span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneCaca</span><span class="pln"> content_shell
</span><span class="pun">./</span><span class="kwd">out</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="typ">OzoneCaca</span><span class="pun">/</span><span class="pln">content_shell
</span></pre><p>Note: traditional TTYs are not the ideal browsing experience.<br /> <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Picture of a workstation using Ozone/caca to display the Google home page in a text terminal" /></p><h2><a class="h" name="Communication" href="#Communication"><span></span></a>Communication</h2><p>There is a public mailing list: <a href="https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/forum/#!forum/ozone-dev">ozone-dev@chromium.org</a></p></div></div></div><footer class="Site-footer"><div class="Footer"><div class="Footer-poweredBy">Powered by <a href="https://gerrit.googlesource.com/gitiles/">Gitiles</a></div><div class="Footer-links"><a class="Footer-link" href="/chromium/src/+show/master/docs/ozone_overview.md">source</a><a class="Footer-link" href="/chromium/src/+log/master/docs/ozone_overview.md">log</a><a class="Footer-link" href="/chromium/src/+blame/master/docs/ozone_overview.md">blame</a></ul></div></footer><script>(function(i,s,o,g,r,a,m){i['GoogleAnalyticsObject']=r;i[r]=i[r]||function(){(i[r].q=i[r].q||[]).push(arguments)},i[r].l=1*new Date();a=s.createElement(o), m=s.getElementsByTagName(o)[0];a.async=1;a.src=g;m.parentNode.insertBefore(a,m)})(window,document,'script','//www.google-analytics.com/analytics.js','ga'); ga('create', 'UA-55762617-15', 'auto'); ga('send', 'pageview', {title: 'Ozone Overview'});</script></body></html>
